-- MODULE 5: Areas, Volumes and Curves
INSERT INTO fs_study_modules (id, module_number, title, description, week_range, exam_weight_percent, key_topics, key_formulas, content_sections, prerequisite_module, passing_score, question_count, icon, xp_reward)
VALUES (
  'f5000005-0000-0000-0000-000000000005',
  5,
  'Areas, Volumes and Curves',
  'Coordinate area computation, DMD method, volume calculations, and horizontal and vertical curve design.',
  'Weeks 9-10',
  15,
  ARRAY['Coordinate area','DMD method','Average end area','Prismoidal formula','Horizontal curves','Vertical curves'],
  '[{"name":"Coordinate Area","formula":"2A = sum(Xi * (Yi+1 - Yi-1))"},{"name":"Average End Area Volume","formula":"V = L * (A1 + A2) / 2"},{"name":"Radius of Curve","formula":"R = 5729.578 / D"},{"name":"Tangent Length","formula":"T = R * tan(delta/2)"},{"name":"Curve Length","formula":"L = 100 * delta / D"}]'::jsonb,
  '[{"type":"overview","title":"Module Overview","content":"Areas, Volumes and Curves covers 15% of the FS exam and combines computational geometry with route design. You must be proficient in computing areas from coordinates, calculating earthwork volumes, and solving horizontal and vertical curve problems.\n\nThe coordinate area method (also called the shoelace or cross-multiply method) is the most efficient way to compute the area of a polygon from its vertex coordinates. The DMD (Double Meridian Distance) method is an alternative that was historically important and still appears on exams.\n\nVolume calculations are essential for earthwork on construction projects. The average end area method is simpler but always overestimates the true volume. The prismoidal formula provides a more accurate result by accounting for the middle cross section. You should know when each method is appropriate.\n\nHorizontal and vertical curve design is a major topic. Horizontal curves are circular arcs connecting two tangent lines. You must know the relationships between radius, degree of curve, tangent length, curve length, and external distance. Vertical curves are parabolic curves connecting two grade lines, and you must be able to find the high or low point and compute elevations along the curve."},{"type":"concepts","title":"Key Concepts","content":"## Coordinate Area Method\n\nArrange coordinates in a table. Cross-multiply: 2A = sum of (X_i * Y_(i+1)) - sum of (X_(i+1) * Y_i). A negative result indicates clockwise traversal. Take the absolute value and divide by 2 for area. This method works for any polygon.\n\n## Volume Computation\n\nAverage End Area: V = L(A1+A2)/2 where L = distance between cross sections, A1 and A2 are the end areas. Always overestimates. Prismoidal Formula: V = L(A1 + 4Am + A2)/6 where Am = area at the middle. More accurate.\n\n## Horizontal Curves\n\nDefined by radius R or degree of curve D (arc definition: angle subtended by a 100-ft arc). Key relationships: R = 5729.578/D, T = R*tan(delta/2), L = 100*delta/D, E = R*(sec(delta/2)-1), M = R*(1-cos(delta/2)). The PC (point of curvature) and PT (point of tangency) define the curve limits.\n\n## Vertical Curves\n\nParabolic curves connecting grade lines g1 and g2. Length L is measured horizontally in stations. Rate of change r = (g2-g1)/L. High/low point at x = -g1/r from BVC. Elevation at any point: y = y_BVC + g1*x + (r/2)*x^2."},{"type":"formulas","title":"Essential Formulas","content":"**Coordinate Area:** 2A = |sum(Xi*(Yi+1 - Yi-1))| or cross-multiply method.\n\n**Average End Area:** V = L*(A1+A2)/2. Simple but overestimates.\n\n**Prismoidal:** V = L*(A1+4Am+A2)/6. Most accurate.\n\n**Degree of Curve:** R = 5729.578/D (arc definition).\n\n**Tangent Length:** T = R*tan(delta/2).\n\n**Curve Length:** L = 100*delta/D or L = R*delta (delta in radians).\n\n**External Distance:** E = R*(sec(delta/2) - 1).\n\n**Vertical Curve High/Low Point:** x = -g1*L/(g2-g1) from BVC."},{"type":"examples","title":"Worked Examples","content":"**Example 1: Coordinate Area**\nTriangle with vertices (0,0), (100,0), (50,86.6).\n2A = |0*(0-86.6) + 100*(86.6-0) + 50*(0-0)| = |0 + 8660 + 0| = 8660\nA = 4330 sq ft\n\n**Example 2: Horizontal Curve**\nR = 1000 ft, delta = 30 degrees.\nT = 1000*tan(15) = 1000*0.2679 = 267.95 ft\nL = 1000*(30*pi/180) = 1000*0.5236 = 523.60 ft\n\n**Example 3: Vertical Curve High Point**\nL = 400 ft, g1 = +4%, g2 = -2%.\nr = (-2-4)/400 = -6/400 = -0.015%/ft\nHigh point from BVC: x = -4/(-0.015) = 266.67 ft"}]'::jsonb,
  4,
  70,
  20,
  'üìä',
  550
)
